10590840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Evaluation of natural language processing ==@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10590850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Objectives===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10590860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The goal of NLP evaluation is to measure one or more ''qualities'' of an algorithm or a system, in order to determine if (or to what extent) the system answers the goals of its designers, or the needs of its users.@1@41@@oe@30-11-2008
10590870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Research in NLP evaluation has received considerable attention, because the definition of proper evaluation criteria is one way to specify precisely an NLP problem, going thus beyond the vagueness of tasks defined only as ''language understanding'' or ''language generation''.@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10590880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A precise set of evaluation criteria, which includes mainly evaluation data and evaluation metrics, enables several teams to compare their solutions to a given NLP problem.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10590890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Short history of evaluation in NLP===@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10590900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The first evaluation campaign on written texts seems to be a campaign dedicated to message understanding in 1987 (Pallet 1998).@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10590910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Then, the Parseval/GEIG project compared phrase-structure grammars (Black 1991).@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10590920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A series of campaigns within Tipster project were realized on tasks like summarization, translation and searching (Hirshman 1998).@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10590930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In 1994, in Germany, the Morpholympics compared German taggers.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10590940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Then, the Senseval and Romanseval campaigns were conducted with the objectives of semantic disambiguation.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10590950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In 1996, the Sparkle campaign compared syntactic parsers in four different languages (English, French, German and Italian).@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10590960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In France, the Grace project compared a set of 21 taggers for French in 1997 (Adda 1999).@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10590970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In 2004, during the [[Technolangue/Easy]] project, 13 parsers for French were compared.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10590980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Large-scale evaluation of dependency parsers were performed in the context of the CoNLL shared tasks in 2006 and 2007.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10590990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In Italy, the evalita campaign was conducted in 2007 to compare various tools for Italian [http://evalita.itc.it evalita web site].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10591000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In France, within the ANR-Passage project (end of 2007), 10 parsers for French were compared [http://atoll.inria.fr/passage/ passage web site].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10591010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Adda G., Mariani J., Paroubek P., Rajman M. 1999 L'action GRACE d'évaluation de l'assignation des parties du discours pour le français.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10591020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Langues vol-2@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10591030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Black E., Abney S., Flickinger D., Gdaniec C., Grishman R., Harrison P., Hindle D., Ingria R., Jelinek F., Klavans J., Liberman M., Marcus M., Reukos S., Santoni B., Strzalkowski T. 1991 A procedure for quantitatively comparing the syntactic coverage of English grammars.@1@42@@oe@30-11-2008
10591040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@DARPA Speech and Natural Language Workshop@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10591050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hirshman L. 1998 Language understanding evaluation: lessons learned from MUC and ATIS.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10591060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@LREC Granada@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10591070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Pallet D.S. 1998 The NIST role in automatic speech recognition benchmark tests.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10591080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@LREC Granada@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10591090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Different types of evaluation===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10591100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Depending on the evaluation procedures, a number of distinctions are traditionally made in NLP evaluation.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10591110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Intrinsic vs. extrinsic evaluation@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10591120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Intrinsic evaluation considers an isolated NLP system and characterizes its performance mainly with respect to a ''gold standard'' result, pre-defined by the evaluators.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10591130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Extrinsic evaluation, also called ''evaluation in use'' considers the NLP system in a more complex setting, either as an embedded system or serving a precise function for a human user.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10591140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The extrinsic performance of the system is then characterized in terms of its utility with respect to the overall task of the complex system or the human user.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10591150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Black-box vs. glass-box evaluation@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10591160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Black-box evaluation requires one to run an NLP system on a given data set and to measure a number of parameters related to the quality of the process (speed, reliability, resource consumption) and, most importantly, to the quality of the result (e.g. the accuracy of data annotation or the fidelity of a translation).@1@53@@oe@30-11-2008
10591170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Glass-box evaluation looks at the design of the system, the algorithms that are implemented, the linguistic resources it uses (e.g. vocabulary size), etc.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10591180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Given the complexity of NLP problems, it is often difficult to predict performance only on the basis of glass-box evaluation, but this type of evaluation is more informative with respect to error analysis or future developments of a system.@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10591190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Automatic vs. manual evaluation@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10591200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In many cases, automatic procedures can be defined to evaluate an NLP system by comparing its output with the gold standard (or desired) one.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10591210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Although the cost of producing the gold standard can be quite high, automatic evaluation can be repeated as often as needed without much additional costs (on the same input data).@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10591220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, for many NLP problems, the definition of a gold standard is a complex task, and can prove impossible when inter-annotator agreement is insufficient.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10591230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Manual evaluation is performed by human judges, which are instructed to estimate the quality of a system, or most often of a sample of its output, based on a number of criteria.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10591240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Although, thanks to their linguistic competence, human judges can be considered as the reference for a number of language processing tasks, there is also considerable variation across their ratings.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10591250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is why automatic evaluation is sometimes referred to as ''objective'' evaluation, while the human kind appears to be more ''subjective.''@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10591260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Shared tasks (Campaigns)===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10591270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[BioCreative]]@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10591280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Message Understanding Conference]]@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10591290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Technolangue/Easy]]@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10591300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Text Retrieval Conference]]@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10591310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Standardization in NLP==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10591320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An ISO sub-committee is working in order to ease interoperability between [[Lexical resource]]s and NLP programs.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10591330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The sub-committee is part of [[ISO/TC37]] and is called ISO/TC37/SC4.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10591340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some ISO standards are already published but most of them are under construction, mainly on lexicon representation (see [[lexical markup framework|LMF]]), annotation and data category registry.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10600010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>Neural network</article>@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10600020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Traditionally, the term '''neural network''' had been used to refer to a network or circuit of [[neuron|biological neurons]].@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10600030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The modern usage of the term often refers to [[artificial neural network]]s, which are composed of [[artificial neuron]]s or nodes.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10600040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus the term has two distinct usages:@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10600050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@# [[Biological neural network]]s are made up of real biological neurons that are connected or functionally-related in the [[peripheral nervous system]] or the [[central nervous system]].@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10600060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the field of [[neuroscience]], they are often identified as groups of neurons that perform a specific physiological function in laboratory analysis.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10600070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@# [[Artificial neural network]]s are made up of interconnecting artificial neurons (programming constructs that mimic the properties of biological neurons).@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10600080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Artificial neural networks may either be used to gain an understanding of biological neural networks, or for solving artificial intelligence problems without necessarily creating a model of a real biological system.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10600090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This article focuses on the relationship between the two concepts; for detailed coverage of the two different concepts refer to the separate articles: [[Biological neural network]] and [[Artificial neural network]].@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10600100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Characterization==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10600110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In general a biological neural network is composed of a group or groups of chemically connected or functionally associated neurons.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10600120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A single neuron may be connected to many other neurons and the total number of neurons and connections in a network may be extensive.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10600130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Connections, called [[synapses]], are usually formed from [[axons]] to [[dendrites]], though dendrodendritic microcircuits and other connections are possible.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10600140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Apart from the electrical signaling, there are other forms of signaling that arise from [[neurotransmitter]] diffusion, which have an effect on electrical signaling.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10600150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As such, neural networks are extremely complex.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10600160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Artificial intelligence]] and [[cognitive modeling]] try to simulate some properties of neural networks.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10600170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While similar in their techniques, the former has the aim of solving particular tasks, while the latter aims to build mathematical models of biological neural systems.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10600180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the [[artificial intelligence]] field, artificial neural networks have been applied successfully to [[speech recognition]], [[image analysis]] and adaptive [[control]], in order to construct [[software agents]] (in [[Video game|computer and video games]]) or [[autonomous robot]]s.@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10600190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Most of the currently employed artificial neural networks for artificial intelligence are based on [[statistical estimation]], [[Optimization (mathematics)|optimization]] and [[control theory]].@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10600200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[cognitive modelling]] field involves the physical or mathematical modeling of the behaviour of neural systems; ranging from the individual neural level (e.g. modelling the spike response curves of neurons to a stimulus), through the neural cluster level (e.g. modelling the release and effects of dopamine in the basal ganglia) to the complete organism (e.g. behavioural modelling of the organism's response to stimuli).@1@63@@oe@30-11-2008
10600210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==The brain, neural networks and computers==@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10600220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Neural networks, as used in artificial intelligence, have traditionally been viewed as simplified models of neural processing in the brain, even though the relation between this model and brain biological architecture is debated.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10600230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A subject of current research in theoretical neuroscience is the question surrounding the degree of complexity and the properties that individual neural elements should have to reproduce something resembling animal intelligence.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10600240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Historically, computers evolved from the [[von Neumann architecture]], which is based on sequential processing and execution of explicit instructions.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10600250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@On the other hand, the origins of neural networks are based on efforts to model information processing in biological systems, which may rely largely on parallel processing as well as implicit instructions based on recognition of patterns of 'sensory' input from external sources.@1@43@@oe@30-11-2008
10600260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In other words, at its very heart a neural network is a complex statistical processor (as opposed to being tasked to sequentially process and execute).@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10600270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Neural networks and artificial intelligence==@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10600280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An ''artificial neural network'' (ANN), also called a ''simulated neural network'' (SNN) or commonly just ''neural network'' (NN) is an interconnected group of [[artificial neuron]]s that uses a [[mathematical model|mathematical or computational model]] for [[information processing]] based on a [[connectionism|connectionistic]] approach to [[computation]].@1@43@@oe@30-11-2008
10600290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In most cases an ANN is an [[adaptive system]] that changes its structure based on external or internal information that flows through the network.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10600300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In more practical terms neural networks are [[non-linear]] [[statistical]] [[data modeling]] or [[decision making]] tools.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10600310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They can be used to model complex relationships between inputs and outputs or to [[Pattern recognition|find patterns]] in data.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10600320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Background===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10600330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An [[artificial neural network]] involves a network of simple processing elements ([[artificial neurons]]) which can exhibit complex global behaviour, determined by the connections between the processing elements and element parameters.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10600340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@One classical type of artificial neural network is the [[Hopfield net]].@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10600350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In a neural network model simple [[Node (neural networks)|nodes]], which can be called variously "neurons", "neurodes", "Processing Elements" (PE) or "units", are connected together to form a network of nodes &mdash; hence the term "neural network".@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10600360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While a neural network does not have to be adaptive ''per se'', its practical use comes with algorithms designed to alter the strength (weights) of the connections in the network to produce a desired signal flow.@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10600370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In modern [[Neural network software|software implementations]] of artificial neural networks the approach inspired by biology has more or less been abandoned for a more practical approach based on statistics and signal processing.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10600380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In some of these systems neural networks, or parts of neural networks (such as [[artificial neuron]]s) are used as components in larger systems that combine both adaptive and non-adaptive elements.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10600390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The concept of a neural network appears to have first been proposed by [[Alan Turing]] in his 1948 paper "Intelligent Machinery".@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10600400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Applications===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10600410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The utility of artificial neural network models lies in the fact that they can be used to infer a function from observations and also to use it.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10600420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is particularly useful in applications where the complexity of the data or task makes the design of such a function by hand impractical.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10600430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Real life applications====@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10600440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The tasks to which artificial neural networks are applied tend to fall within the following broad categories:@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10600450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*[[Function approximation]], or [[regression analysis]], including [[time series prediction]] and modelling.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10600460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*[[Statistical classification|Classification]], including [[Pattern recognition|pattern]] and sequence recognition, novelty detection and sequential decision making.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10600470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*[[Data processing]], including filtering, clustering, [[blind signal separation]] and compression.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10600480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Application areas include system identification and control (vehicle control, process control), game-playing and decision making (backgammon, chess, racing), pattern recognition (radar systems, face identification, object recognition, etc.), sequence recognition (gesture, speech, handwritten text recognition), medical diagnosis, financial applications, [[data mining]] (or knowledge discovery in databases, "KDD"), visualization and [[e-mail spam]] filtering.@1@51@@oe@30-11-2008
10600490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Neural network software===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10600500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Main article:'' [[Neural network software]]@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10600510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@'''Neural network software''' is used to [[Simulation|simulate]], [[research]], [[Software development|develop]] and apply [[artificial neural network]]s, [[biological neural network]]s and in some cases a wider array of [[adaptive system]]s.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10600520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Learning paradigms====@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10600530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are three major learning paradigms, each corresponding to a particular abstract learning task.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10600540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These are [[supervised learning]], [[unsupervised learning]] and [[reinforcement learning]].@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10600550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Usually any given type of network architecture can be employed in any of those tasks.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10600560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@;Supervised learning@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10600570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[supervised learning]], we are given a set of example pairs <math> (x, y), x \\in X, y \\in Y</math> and the aim is to find a function <math>f</math> in the allowed class of functions that matches the examples.@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10600580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In other words, we wish to ''infer'' how the mapping implied by the data and the cost function is related to the mismatch between our mapping and the data.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10600590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@;Unsupervised learning@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10600600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[unsupervised learning]] we are given some data <math>x</math>, and a cost function which is to be minimized which can be any function of <math>x</math> and the network's output, <math>f</math>.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10600610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The cost function is determined by the task formulation.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10600620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Most applications fall within the domain of [[estimation problems]] such as [[statistical modeling]], [[Data compression|compression]], [[Mail filter|filtering]], [[blind source separation]] and [[data clustering|clustering]].@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10600630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@;Reinforcement learning@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10600640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[reinforcement learning]], data <math>x</math> is usually not given, but generated by an agent's interactions with the environment.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10600650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@At each point in time <math>t</math>, the agent performs an action <math>y_t</math> and the environment generates an observation <math>x_t</math> and an instantaneous cost <math>c_t</math>, according to some (usually unknown) dynamics.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10600660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The aim is to discover a ''policy'' for selecting actions that minimises some measure of a long-term cost, i.e. the expected cumulative cost.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10600670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The environment's dynamics and the long-term cost for each policy are usually unknown, but can be estimated.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10600680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@ANNs are frequently used in reinforcement learning as part of the overall algorithm.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10600690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Tasks that fall within the paradigm of reinforcement learning are [[control]] problems, [[game]]s and other [[sequential decision making]] tasks.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10600700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Learning algorithms====@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10600710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are many algorithms for training neural networks; most of them can be viewed as a straightforward application of [[Optimization (mathematics)|optimization]] theory and [[statistical estimation]].@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10600720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Evolutionary computation]] methods, [[simulated annealing]], [[Expectation-Maximization|expectation maximization]] and [[non-parametric methods]] are among other commonly used methods for training neural networks.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10600730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@See also [[machine learning]].@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10600740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Recent developments in this field also saw the use of [[particle swarm optimization]] and other [[swarm intelligence]] techniques used in the training of neural networks.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10600750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Neural networks and neuroscience==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10600760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Theoretical and [[computational neuroscience]] is the field concerned with the theoretical analysis and computational modeling of biological neural systems.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10600770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Since neural systems are intimately related to cognitive processes and behaviour, the field is closely related to cognitive and behavioural modeling.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10600780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The aim of the field is to create models of biological neural systems in order to understand how biological systems work.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10600790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@To gain this understanding, neuroscientists strive to make a link between observed biological processes (data), biologically plausible mechanisms for neural processing and learning ([[biological neural network]] models) and theory (statistical learning theory and [[information theory]]).@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10600800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Types of models ===@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10600810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Many models are used in the field, each defined at a different level of abstraction and trying to model different aspects of neural systems.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10600820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They range from models of the short-term behaviour of [[biological neuron models|individual neurons]], through models of how the dynamics of neural circuitry arise from interactions between individual neurons, to models of how behaviour can arise from abstract neural modules that represent complete subsystems.@1@43@@oe@30-11-2008
10600830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These include models of the long-term and short-term plasticity of neural systems and its relation to learning and memory, from the individual neuron to the system level.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10600840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Current research===@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10600850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While initially research had been concerned mostly with the electrical characteristics of neurons, a particularly important part of the investigation in recent years has been the exploration of the role of [[neuromodulators]] such as [[dopamine]], [[acetylcholine]], and [[serotonin]] on behaviour and learning.@1@42@@oe@30-11-2008
10600860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Biophysics|Biophysical]] models, such as [[BCM theory]], have been important in understanding mechanisms for [[synaptic plasticity]], and have had applications in both computer science and neuroscience.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10600870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Research is ongoing in understanding the computational algorithms used in the brain, with some recent biological evidence for [[radial basis networks]] and [[neural backpropagation]] as mechanisms for processing data.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10600880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==History of the neural network analogy==@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10600890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The concept of neural networks started in the late-1800s as an effort to describe how the human mind performed.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10600900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These ideas started being applied to computational models with the [[Perceptron]].@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10600910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In early 1950s [[Friedrich Hayek]] was one of the first to posit the idea of [[spontaneous order]] in the brain arising out of decentralized networks of simple units (neurons).@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10600920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the late 1940s, [[Donald Hebb]] made one of the first hypotheses for a mechanism of neural plasticity (i.e. learning), [[Hebbian learning]].@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10600930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hebbian learning is considered to be a 'typical' unsupervised learning rule and it (and variants of it) was an early model for [[long term potentiation]].@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10600940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[Perceptron]] is essentially a linear classifier for classifying data <math> x \\in R^n</math> specified by parameters <math>w \\in R^n, b \\in R</math> and an output function <math>f = w'x + b</math>.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10600950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Its parameters are adapted with an ad-hoc rule similar to stochastic steepest gradient descent.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10600960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Because the [[inner product]] is a [[linear operator]] in the input space, the Perceptron can only perfectly classify a set of data for which different classes are [[linearly separable]] in the input space, while it often fails completely for non-separable data.@1@41@@oe@30-11-2008
10600970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While the development of the algorithm initially generated some enthusiasm, partly because of its apparent relation to biological mechanisms, the later discovery of this inadequacy caused such models to be abandoned until the introduction of non-linear models into the field.@1@40@@oe@30-11-2008
10600980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[Cognitron]] (1975) was an early multilayered neural network with a training algorithm.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10600990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The actual structure of the network and the methods used to set the interconnection weights change from one neural strategy to another, each with its advantages and disadvantages.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10601000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Networks can propagate information in one direction only, or they can bounce back and forth until self-activation at a node occurs and the network settles on a final state.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10601010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The ability for bi-directional flow of inputs between neurons/nodes was produced with the [[Hopfield net|Hopfield's network]] (1982), and specialization of these node layers for specific purposes was introduced through the first [[hybrid neural network|hybrid network]].@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10601020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[connectionism|parallel distributed processing]] of the mid-1980s became popular under the name [[connectionism]].@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10601030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The rediscovery of the [[backpropagation]] algorithm was probably the main reason behind the repopularisation of neural networks after the publication of "Learning Internal Representations by Error Propagation" in 1986 (Though backpropagation itself dates from 1974).@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10601040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The original network utilised multiple layers of weight-sum units of the type <math>f = g(w'x + b)</math>, where <math>g</math> was a [[sigmoid function]] or [[logistic function]] such as used in [[logistic regression]].@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10601050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Training was done by a form of stochastic steepest gradient descent.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10601060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The employment of the chain rule of differentiation in deriving the appropriate parameter updates results in an algorithm that seems to 'backpropagate errors', hence the nomenclature.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10601070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However it is essentially a form of gradient descent.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10601080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Determining the optimal parameters in a model of this type is not trivial, and steepest gradient descent methods cannot be relied upon to give the solution without a good starting point.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10601090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In recent times, networks with the same architecture as the backpropagation network are referred to as [[Multilayer perceptron|Multi-Layer Perceptrons]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10601100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This name does not impose any limitations on the type of algorithm used for learning.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10601110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The backpropagation network generated much enthusiasm at the time and there was much controversy about whether such learning could be implemented in the brain or not, partly because a mechanism for reverse signalling was not obvious at the time, but most importantly because there was no plausible source for the 'teaching' or 'target' signal.@1@54@@oe@30-11-2008
10601120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Criticism==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10601130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[A. K. Dewdney]], a former ''[[Scientific American]]'' columnist, wrote in 1997, ''“Although neural nets do solve a few toy problems, their powers of computation are so limited that I am surprised anyone takes them seriously as a general problem-solving tool.”''@1@40@@oe@30-11-2008
10601140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(Dewdney, p.82)@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10601150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Arguments against Dewdney's position are that neural nets have been successfully used to solve many complex and diverse tasks, ranging from autonomously flying aircraft[http://www.nasa.gov/centers/dryden/news/NewsReleases/2003/03-49.html] to detecting credit card fraud[http://www.visa.ca/en/about/visabenefits/innovation.cfm].@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10601160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Technology writer [[Roger Bridgman]] commented on Dewdney's statements about neural nets:@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10601170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<blockquote> Neural networks, for instance, are in the dock not only because they have been hyped to high heaven, (what hasn't?) but also because you could create a successful net without understanding how it worked: the bunch of numbers that captures its behaviour would in all probability be "an opaque, unreadable table...valueless as a scientific resource".@1@56@@oe@30-11-2008
10601180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In spite of his emphatic declaration that science is not technology, Dewdney seems here to pillory neural nets as bad science when most of those devising them are just trying to be good engineers.@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10601190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An unreadable table that a useful machine could read would still be well worth having.</blockquote>@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>N-gram</article>@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10610020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An '''''n''-gram''' is a sub-sequence of ''n'' items from a given [[sequence]]. ''n''-grams are used in various areas of statistical [[natural language processing]] and genetic sequence analysis.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10610030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The items in question can be letters, words or [[base pairs]] according to the application.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An ''n''-gram of size 1 is a "[[unigram]]"; size 2 is a "[[bigram]]" (or, more etymologically sound but less commonly used, a "digram"); size 3 is a "[[trigram]]"; and size 4 or more is simply called an "''n''-gram".@1@38@@oe@30-11-2008
10610050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some [[language model]]s built from n-grams are "(''n''&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;1)-order [[Markov_chain|Markov model]]s".@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10610060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Examples==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10610070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Here are examples of '''''word''''' level 3-grams and 4-grams (and counts of the number of times they appeared) from the [[N-gram#Google_use_of_N-gram|Google n-gram corpus]].@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10610080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*ceramics collectables collectibles (55)@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*ceramics collectables fine (130)@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*ceramics collected by (52)@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*ceramics collectible pottery (50)@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*ceramics collectibles cooking (45)@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@4-grams@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10610140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*serve as the incoming (92)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*serve as the incubator (99)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*serve as the independent (794)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*serve as the index (223)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*serve as the indication (72)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*serve as the indicator (120)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==''n''-gram models==@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10610210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An '''''n''-gram model''' models sequences, notably natural languages, using the statistical properties of ''n''-grams.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10610220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This idea can be traced to an experiment by [[Claude Shannon]]'s work in [[information theory]].@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@His question was, given a sequence of letters (for example, the sequence "for ex"), what is the [[likelihood]] of the next letter?@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10610240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@From training data, one can derive a [[probability distribution]] for the next letter given a history of size <math>n</math>: ''a'' = 0.4, ''b'' = 0.00001, ''c'' = 0, ....; where the probabilities of all possible "next-letters" sum to 1.0.@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10610250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@More concisely, an ''n''-gram model predicts <math>x_{i}</math> based on <math>x_{i-1}, x_{i-2}, \\dots, x_{i-n}</math>.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10610260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In Probability terms, this is nothing but <math>P(x_{i} | x_{i-1}, x_{i-2}, \\dots, x_{i-n})</math>.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10610270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@When used for [[language model|language modeling]] independence assumptions are made so that each word depends only on the last ''n'' words.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10610280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This [[Markov model]] is used as an approximation of the true underlying language.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10610290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This assumption is important because it massively simplifies the problem of learning the language model from data.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10610300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In addition, because of the open nature of language, it is common to group words unknown to the language model together.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10610310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''n''-gram models are widely used in statistical [[natural language processing]].@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10610320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[speech recognition]], [[phonemes]] and sequences of phonemes are modeled using a ''n''-gram distribution.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10610330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For parsing, words are modeled such that each ''n''-gram is composed of ''n'' words.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10610340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For [[language recognition]], sequences of letters are modeled for different languages.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10610350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For a sequence of words, (for example "the dog smelled like a skunk"), the trigrams would be: "the dog smelled", "dog smelled like", "smelled like a", and "like a skunk".@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10610360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For sequences of characters, the 3-grams (sometimes referred to as "trigrams") that can be generated from "good morning" are "goo", "ood", "od ", "d m", " mo", "mor" and so forth.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10610370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some practitioners preprocess strings to remove spaces, most simply collapse whitespace to a single space while preserving paragraph marks.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10610380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Punctuation is also commonly reduced or removed by preprocessing. ''n''-grams can also be used for sequences of words or, in fact, for almost any type of data.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10610390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They have been used for example for extracting features for clustering large sets of satellite earth images and for determining what part of the Earth a particular image came from.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10610400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They have also been very successful as the first pass in genetic sequence search and in the identification of which species short sequences of DNA were taken from.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10610410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@N-gram models are often criticized because they lack any explicit representation of long range dependency.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While it is true that the only explicit dependency range is (n-1) tokens for an n-gram model, it is also true that the effective range of dependency is significantly longer than this although long range correlations drop exponentially with distance for any Markov model.@1@44@@oe@30-11-2008
10610430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Alternative Markov language models that incorporate some degree of local state can exhibit very long range dependencies.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10610440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is often done using hand-crafted state variables that represent, for instance, the position in a sentence, the general topic of discourse or a grammatical state variable.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10610450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some of the best parsers of English currently in existence are roughly of this form.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another criticism that has been leveled is that Markov models of language, including n-gram models, do not explicitly capture the performance/competence distinction introduced by [[Noam Chomsky]].@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10610470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This criticism fails to explain why parsers that are the best at parsing text seem to uniformly lack any such distinction and most even lack any clear distinction between semantics and syntax.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10610480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Most proponents of n-gram and related language models opt for a fairly pragmatic approach to language modeling that emphasizes empirical results over theoretical purity.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10610490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==''n''-grams for approximate matching==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''n''-grams can also be used for efficient approximate matching.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10610510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@By converting a sequence of items to a set of ''n''-grams, it can be embedded in a [[vector space]] (in other words, represented as a [[histogram]]), thus allowing the sequence to be compared to other sequences in an efficient manner.@1@40@@oe@30-11-2008
10610520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, if we convert strings with only letters in the English alphabet into 3-grams, we get a <math>26^3</math>-dimensional space (the first dimension measures the number of occurrences of "aaa", the second "aab", and so forth for all possible combinations of three letters).@1@43@@oe@30-11-2008
10610530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Using this representation, we lose information about the string.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10610540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, both the strings "abcba" and "bcbab" give rise to exactly the same 2-grams.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, we know empirically that if two strings of real text have a similar vector representation (as measured by [[dot product|cosine distance]]) then they are likely to be similar.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10610560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Other metrics have also been applied to vectors of ''n''-grams with varying, sometimes better, results.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example [[z-score]]s have been used to compare documents by examining how many standard deviations each ''n''-gram differs from its mean occurrence in a large collection, or [[text corpus]], of documents (which form the "background" vector).@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10610580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the event of small counts, the [[g-score]] may give better results for comparing alternative models.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10610590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is also possible to take a more principled approach to the statistics of ''n''-grams, modeling similarity as the likelihood that two strings came from the same source directly in terms of a problem in [[Bayesian inference]].@1@37@@oe@30-11-2008
10610600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Other applications==@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10610610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''n''-grams find use in several areas of computer science, [[computational linguistics]], and applied mathematics.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10610620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They have been used to:@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* design [[kernel (mathematics)|kernels]] that allow [[machine learning]] algorithms such as [[support vector machine]]s to learn from string data@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10610640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* find likely candidates for the correct spelling of a misspelled word@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10610650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* improve compression in [[data compression|compression algorithms]] where a small area of data requires ''n''-grams of greater length@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10610660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* assess the probability of a given word sequence appearing in text of a language of interest in pattern recognition systems, [[speech recognition]], OCR ([[optical character recognition]]), [[Intelligent Character Recognition]] ([[ICR]]), [[machine translation]] and similar applications@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10610670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* improve retrieval in [[information retrieval]] systems when it is hoped to find similar "documents" (a term for which the conventional meaning is sometimes stretched, depending on the data set) given a single query document and a database of reference documents@1@41@@oe@30-11-2008
10610680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* improve retrieval performance in genetic sequence analysis as in the [[BLAST]] family of programs@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10610690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* identify the language a text is in or the species a small sequence of DNA was taken from@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10610700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* predict letters or words at random in order to create text, as in the [[dissociated press]] algorithm.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10610710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Bias-versus-variance trade-off ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@What goes into picking the ''n'' for the ''n''-gram?@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10610730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are problems of balance weight between ''infrequent grams'' (for example, if a proper name appeared in the training data) and ''frequent grams''.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10610740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Also, items not seen in the training data will be given a [[probability]] of 0.0 without [[smoothing]].@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10610750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For unseen but plausible data from a sample, one can introduce [[pseudocount]]s.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10610760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Pseudocounts are generally motivated on Bayesian grounds.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10610770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Smoothing techniques ===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Linear interpolation]] (e.g., taking the [[weighted mean]] of the unigram, bigram, and trigram)@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10610790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Good-Turing]] discounting@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10610800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Witten-Bell discounting]]@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10610810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Katz's back-off model]] (trigram)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10610820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Google use of N-gram==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10610830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Google]] uses n-gram models for a variety of R&D projects, such as [[statistical machine translation]], [[speech recognition]], [[Spell checker|checking spelling]], [[entity detection]], and [[information extraction|data mining]].@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10610840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In September of 2006 [http://googleresearch.blogspot.com/2006/08/all-our-n-gram-are-belong-to-you.html Google announced] that they made their n-grams [http://www.ldc.upenn.edu/Catalog/CatalogEntry.jsp?catalogId=LDC2006T13 public] at the [[Linguistic Data Consortium]] ([http://www.ldc.upenn.edu/ LDC]).@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10620010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>Noun</article>@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10620020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[linguistics]], a '''noun''' is a member of a large, [[open class (linguistics)|open]] [[lexical category]] whose members can occur as the main word in the [[subject (grammar)|subject]] of a [[clause]], the [[object (grammar)|object]] of a [[verb]], or the object of a [[preposition]].@1@42@@oe@30-11-2008
10620030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Lexical categories are defined in terms of how their members combine with other kinds of expressions.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10620040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The syntactic rules for nouns differ from language to language.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10620050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[English language|English]], nouns may be defined as those words which can occur with articles and [[adjective|attributive adjectives]] and can function as the [[phrase|head]] of a [[noun phrase]].@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10620060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[traditional grammar|traditional]] English grammar, the noun is one of the eight [[parts of speech]].@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10620070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==History==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10620080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The word comes from the [[Latin]] ''nomen'' meaning "[[name]]".@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10620090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Word classes like nouns were first described by the Sanskrit grammarian [[Panini (grammarian)|{{IAST|Pāṇini}}]] and ancient Greeks like [[Dionysios Thrax]]; and were defined in terms of their [[morphology (linguistics)|morphological]] properties.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10620100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, in Ancient Greek, nouns inflect for [[case (grammar)|grammatical case]], such as dative or accusative.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10620110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Verb]]s, on the other hand, inflect for [[grammatical tense|tenses]], such as past, present or future, while nouns do not.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10620120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Aristotle]] also had a notion of ''onomata'' (nouns) and ''rhemata'' (verbs) which, however, does not exactly correspond with modern notions of nouns and verbs.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10620130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Vinokurova 2005 has a more detailed discussion of the historical origin of the notion of a noun.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10620140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Different definitions of nouns==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10620150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Expressions of [[natural language]] have properties at different levels.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10620160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They have ''formal'' properties, like what kinds of [[morphology (linguistics)|morphological]] [[prefix]]es or [[suffix]]es they take and what kinds of other expressions they combine with; but they also have [[semantics|semantic]] properties, i.e. properties pertaining to their meaning.@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10620170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The definition of a noun at the outset of this page is thus a ''formal'', traditional grammatical definition.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10620180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@That definition, for the most part, is considered uncontroversial and furnishes the propensity for certain language users to effectively distinguish most nouns from non-nouns.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10620190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, it has the disadvantage that it does not apply to nouns in all languages.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10620200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example in [[Russian language|Russian]], there are no definite articles, so one cannot define nouns as words that are modified by definite articles.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10620210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are also several attempts of defining nouns in terms of their [[semantics|semantic]] properties.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10620220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Many of these are controversial, but some are discussed below.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10620230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Names for things===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10620240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[Traditional grammar|traditional school grammars]], one often encounters the definition of nouns that they are all and only those expressions that refer to a ''person'', ''place'', ''thing'', ''event'', ''substance'', ''quality'', or ''idea'', etc.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10620250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is a ''semantic'' definition.@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10620260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It has been criticized by contemporary linguists as being uninformative.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10620270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Contemporary linguists generally agree that one cannot successfully define nouns (or other grammatical categories) in terms of what sort of ''object in the world'' they ''[[reference|refer]] to'' or ''[[signification|signify]]''.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10620280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Part of the [[conundrum]] is that the definition makes use of relatively ''general'' nouns ("thing", "phenomenon", "event") to define what nouns ''are''.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10620290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The existence of such ''general'' nouns demonstrates that nouns refer to entities that are organized in [[taxonomy|taxonomic]] [[hierarchies]].@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10620300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@But other kinds of expressions are also organized into such structured taxonomic relationships.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10620310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example the verbs "stroll","saunter", "stride", and "tread" are more specific words than the more ''general'' "walk".@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10620320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Moreover, "walk" is more specific than the verb "move", which, in turn, is less general than "change".@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10620330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@But it is unlikely that such taxonomic relationships can be used to ''define'' nouns and verbs.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10620340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@We cannot ''define'' verbs as those words that refer to "changes" or "states", for example, because the nouns ''change'' and ''state'' probably refer to such things, but, of course, aren't verbs.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10620350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Similarly, nouns like "invasion", "meeting", or "collapse" refer to things that are "done" or "happen".@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10620360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In fact, an influential [[theory]] has it that verbs like "kill" or "die" refer to events, which is among the sort of thing that nouns are supposed to refer to.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10620370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The point being made here is not that this view of verbs is wrong, but rather that this property of verbs is a poor basis for a ''definition'' of this category, just like the property of ''having wheels'' is a poor basis for a definition of cars (some things that have wheels, such as my suitcase or a jumbo jet, aren't cars).@1@62@@oe@30-11-2008
10620380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Similarly, adjectives like "yellow" or "difficult" might be thought to refer to qualities, and adverbs like "outside" or "upstairs" seem to refer to places, which are also among the sorts of things nouns can refer to.@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10620390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@But verbs, adjectives and adverbs are not nouns, and nouns aren't verbs, adjectives or adverbs.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10620400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@One might argue that "definitions" of this sort really rely on speakers' prior intuitive knowledge of what nouns, verbs and adjectives are, and, so don't really add anything over and beyond this.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10620410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Speakers' intuitive knowledge of such things might plausibly be based on ''formal'' criteria, such as the traditional grammatical definition of English nouns aforementioned.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10620420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Prototypically referential expressions===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10620430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another semantic definition of nouns is that they are ''prototypically referential.''@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10620440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@That definition is also not very helpful in distinguishing actual nouns from verbs.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10620450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@But it may still correctly identify a core property of nounhood.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10620460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, we will tend to use nouns like "fool" and "car" when we wish to refer to fools and cars, respectively.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10620470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The notion that this is '''prototypical''' reflects the fact that such nouns can be used, even though nothing with the corresponding property is referred to:@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10620480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:John is no '''fool'''.@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10620490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:If I had a '''car''', I'd go to Marrakech.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10620500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The first sentence above doesn't refer to any fools, nor does the second one refer to any particular car.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10620510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Predicates with identity criteria===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10620520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The British logician [[Peter Thomas Geach]] proposed a very subtle semantic definition of nouns.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10620530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@He noticed that adjectives like "same" can modify nouns, but no other kinds of parts of speech, like [[verbs]] or [[adjectives]].@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10620540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Not only that, but there also doesn't seem to be any ''other'' expressions with similar meaning that can modify verbs and adjectives.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10620550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Consider the following examples.@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10620560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@: Good: John and Bill participated in the '''same''' fight.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10620570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@: Bad:@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10620580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*John and Bill '''samely''' fought.@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10620590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There is no English adverb "samely".@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10620600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In some other languages, like Czech, however there are adverbs corresponding to "samely".@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10620610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hence, in Czech, the translation of the last sentence would be fine; however, it would mean that John and Bill fought ''in the same way'': not that they participated in the ''same fight''.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10620620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Geach proposed that we could explain this, if nouns denote logical [[predicate (grammar)|predicate]]s with '''identity criteria'''.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10620630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An identity criterion would allow us to conclude, for example, that "person x at time 1 is ''the same person'' as person y at time 2".@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10620640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Different nouns can have different identity criteria.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10620650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A well known example of this is due to Gupta:@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10620660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:National Airlines transported 2 million '''passengers''' in 1979.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10620670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:National Airlines transported (at least) 2 million '''persons''' in 1979.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10620680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Given that, in general, all passengers are persons, the last sentence above ought to follow logically from the first one.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10620690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@But it doesn't.@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10620700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is easy to imagine, for example, that on average, every person who travelled with National Airlines in 1979, travelled with them twice.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10620710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In that case, one would say that the airline transported 2 million ''passengers'' but only 1 million ''persons''.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10620720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus, the way that we count ''passengers'' isn't necessarily the same as the way that we count ''persons''.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10620730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Put somewhat differently: At two different times, ''you'' may correspond to two distinct ''passengers'', even though you are one and the same person.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10620740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For a precise definition of ''identity criteria'', see Gupta.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10620750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Recently, Baker has proposed that Geach's definition of nouns in terms of identity criteria allows us to ''explain'' the characteristic properties of nouns.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10620760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@He argues that nouns can co-occur with (in-)definite articles and numerals, and are "prototypically referential" ''because'' they are all and only those [[parts of speech]] that provide identity criteria.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10620770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Baker's proposals are quite new, and linguists are still evaluating them.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10620780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Classification of nouns in English==@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10620790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Proper nouns and common nouns===@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10620800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Proper nouns'' (also called ''[[proper name]]s'') are nouns representing unique entities (such as ''London'', ''Universe'' or ''John''), as distinguished from common nouns which describe a class of entities (such as ''city'', ''planet'' or ''person'').@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10620810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[English language|English]] and most other languages that use the [[Latin alphabet]], proper nouns are usually [[capitalization|capitalized]].@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10620820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Languages differ in whether most elements of multiword proper nouns are capitalised (e.g., American English ''House of Representatives'') or only the initial element (e.g., Slovenian ''Državni zbor'' 'National Assembly').@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10620830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[German language|German]], nouns of all types are capitalized.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10620840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The convention of capitalizing ''all'' nouns was previously used in English, but ended circa 1800.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10620850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In America, the shift in capitalization is recorded in several noteworthy documents.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10620860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The end (but not the beginning) of the [[United States Declaration of Independence#Annotated text of the Declaration|Declaration of Independence]] (1776) and all of the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] (1787) show nearly all nouns capitalized, the [[United States Bill of Rights#Text of the Bill of Rights|Bill of Rights]] (1789) capitalizes a few common nouns but not most of them, and the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Thirteenth Constitutional Amendment]] (1865) only capitalizes proper nouns.@1@73@@oe@30-11-2008
10620870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Sometimes the same word can function as both a common noun and a proper noun, where one such entity is special.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10620880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example the common noun ''god'' denotes all deities, while the proper noun ''God'' references the [[monotheism|monotheistic]] [[God]] specifically.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10620890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Owing to the essentially arbitrary nature of [[Orthography|orthographic]] classification and the existence of variant authorities and adopted [[Style guide|''house styles'']], questionable capitalization of words is not uncommon, even in respected newspapers and magazines.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10620900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Most publishers, however, properly require ''consistency'', at least within the same document, in applying their specified standard.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10620910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The common meaning of the word or words constituting a proper noun may be unrelated to the object to which the proper noun refers.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10620920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, someone might be named "Tiger Smith" despite being neither a [[tiger]] nor a [[smith (metalwork)|smith]].@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10620930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For this reason, proper nouns are usually not [[translation|translated]] between languages, although they may be [[transliteration|transliterated]].@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10620940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, the German surname ''Knödel'' becomes ''Knodel'' or ''Knoedel'' in English (not the literal ''Dumpling'').@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10620950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@However, the [[Transliteration|transcription]] of place names and the names of [[monarch]]s, [[pope]]s, and non-contemporary [[author]]s is common and sometimes universal.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10620960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For instance, the [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] word ''Lisboa'' becomes ''[[Lisbon]]'' in [[English language|English]]; the English ''London'' becomes ''Londres'' in French; and the [[ancient Greek|Greek]] ''Aristotelēs'' becomes [[Aristotle]] in English.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10620970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Countable and uncountable nouns===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10620980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Count nouns'' are common nouns that can take a [[plural]], can combine with [[numerals]] or [[quantifiers]] (e.g. "one", "two", "several", "every", "most"), and can take an indefinite article ("a" or "an").@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10620990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples of count nouns are "chair", "nose", and "occasion".@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10621000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Mass nouns'' (or ''non-count nouns'') differ from count nouns in precisely that respect: they can't take plural or combine with number words or quantifiers.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10621010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples from English include "laughter", "cutlery", "helium", and "furniture".@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10621020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, it is not possible to refer to "a furniture" or "three furnitures".@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10621030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is true even though the pieces of furniture comprising "furniture" could be counted.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10621040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus the distinction between mass and count nouns shouldn't be made in terms of what sorts of things the nouns ''refer'' to, but rather in terms of how the nouns ''present'' these entities.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10621050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Collective nouns===@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10621060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Collective nouns'' are nouns that refer to ''groups'' consisting of more than one individual or entity, even when they are inflected for the [[Grammatical number|singular]].@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10621070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples include "committee", "herd", and "school" (of herring).@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10621080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These nouns have slightly different grammatical properties than other nouns.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10621090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, the [[noun phrases]] that they [[head (syntax)|head]] can serve as the [[subject (grammar)|subject]] of a [[collective predicate]], even when they are inflected for the singular.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10621100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A [[collective predicate]] is a predicate that normally can't take a singular subject.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10621110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An example of the latter is "talked to each other".@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10621120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:Good: The '''boys''' talked to each other.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10621130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:Bad: *The '''boy''' talked to each other.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10621140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:Good: The '''committee''' talked to each other.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10621150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Concrete nouns and abstract nouns===@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10621160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Concrete nouns'' refer to [[physical bodies]] which you use at least one of your [[sense]]s to observe.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10621170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For instance, "chair", "apple", or "Janet".@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10621180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Abstract nouns'' on the other hand refer to [[abstract object]]s, that is ideas or concepts, such as "justice" or "hate".@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10621190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While this distinction is sometimes useful, the boundary between the two of them is not always clear; consider, for example, the noun "art".@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10621200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In English, many abstract nouns are formed by adding noun-forming suffixes ("-ness", "-ity", "-tion") to adjectives or verbs.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10621210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples are "happiness", "circulation" and "serenity".@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10621220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Nouns and pronouns==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10621230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Noun phrase]]s can typically be replaced by [[pronoun]]s, such as "he", "it", "which", and "those", in order to avoid repetition or explicit identification, or for other reasons.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10621240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, in the sentence "Janet thought that he was weird", the word "he" is a pronoun standing in place of the name of the person in question.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10621250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The English word ''one'' can replace parts of [[noun phrase]]s, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10621260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An example is given below:@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10621270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@: John's car is newer than ''the one'' that Bill has.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10621280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@But ''one'' can also stand in for bigger subparts of a noun phrase.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10621290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, in the following example, ''one'' can stand in for ''new car''.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10621300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@: This new car is cheaper than ''that one''.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10621310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Substantive as a word for "noun"==@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10621320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Starting with old [[Latin language|Latin]] grammars, many European languages use some form of the word ''substantive'' as the basic term for noun.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10621330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation "s" instead of "n", which may be used for proper nouns instead.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10621340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This corresponds to those grammars in which nouns and adjectives phase into each other in more areas than, for example, the English term [[Predicative_adjective#Predicative_adjective|predicate adjective]] entails.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10621350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics of the adjective.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10621360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An example in English is:@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10621370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@: The ''poor'' you have always with you.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10621380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Similarly, an adjective can also be used for a whole group or organization of people:@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10621390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@: The Socialist ''International''.@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10621400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hence, these words are substantives that are usually adjectives in English.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>Ontology (information science)</article>@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10630020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In both [[computer science]] and [[information science]], an '''ontology''' is a formal representation of a set of concepts within a [[Domain of discourse|domain]] and the relationships between those concepts.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10630030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is used to [[Reasoning|reason]] about the properties of that domain, and may be used to define the domain.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10630040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Ontologies are used in [[artificial intelligence]], the [[Semantic Web]], [[software engineering]], [[biomedical informatics]], [[library science]], and [[information architecture]] as a form of [[knowledge representation]] about the world or some part of it.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10630050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Common components of ontologies include:@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10630060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Individuals: instances or objects (the basic or "ground level" objects)@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Class]]es: [[set (computer science)|set]]s, collections, concepts or types of objects@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Attribute (computing)|Attribute]]s: properties, features, characteristics, or parameters that objects (and classes) can have@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10630090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Relation (mathematics)|Relations]]: ways that classes and objects can be related to one another@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10630100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Function terms: complex structures formed from certain relations that can be used in place of an individual term in a statement@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10630110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Restrictions: formally stated descriptions of what must be true in order for some assertion to be accepted as input@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10630120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Rules: statements in the form of an if-then (antecedent-consequent) sentence that describe the logical inferences that can be drawn from an assertion in a particular form@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10630130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Axioms: assertions (including rules) in a logical form that together comprise the overall theory that the ontology describes in its domain of application.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10630140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This definition differs from that of "axioms" in generative grammar and formal logic.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10630150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In these disciplines, axioms include only statements asserted as ''a priori'' knowledge.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10630160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As used here, "axioms" also include the theory derived from axiomatic statements.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10630170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Event (philosophy)|Events]]: the changing of attributes or relations@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10630180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Ontologies are commonly encoded using [[ontology language]]s.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10630190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Elements ==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10630200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Contemporary ontologies share many structural similarities, regardless of the language in which they are expressed.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10630210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As mentioned above, most ontologies describe individuals (instances), classes (concepts), attributes, and relations.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10630220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In this section each of these components is discussed in turn.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Individuals ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10630240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Individuals (instances) are the basic, "ground level" components of an ontology.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The individuals in an ontology may include concrete objects such as people, animals, tables, automobiles, molecules, and planets, as well as abstract individuals such as numbers and words.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10630260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Strictly speaking, an ontology need not include any individuals, but one of the general purposes of an ontology is to provide a means of classifying individuals, even if those individuals are not explicitly part of the ontology.@1@37@@oe@30-11-2008
10630270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In formal extensional ontologies, only the utterances of words and numbers are considered individuals – the numbers and names themselves are classes.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10630280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In a 4D ontology, an individual is identified by its spatio-temporal extent.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10630290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples of formal extensional ontologies are [[ISO 15926]] and the model in development by the [[IDEAS Group]].@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10630300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Classes ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10630310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Classes &ndash; concepts that are also called ''type'', ''sort'', ''category'', and ''kind'' &ndash; are abstract groups, sets, or collections of objects.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10630320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They may contain individuals, other classes, or a combination of both.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some examples of classes:@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10630340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Person'', the class of all people@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10630350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Vehicle'', the class of all vehicles@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10630360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Car'', the class of all cars@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10630370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Class'', representing the class of all classes@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10630380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Thing'', representing the class of all things@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10630390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Ontologies vary on whether classes can contain other classes, whether a class can belong to itself, whether there is a universal class (that is, a class containing everything), etc.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10630400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Sometimes restrictions along these lines are made in order to avoid certain well-known [[paradox]]es.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10630410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The classes of an ontology may be [[extensional]] or [[intensional]] in nature.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10630420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A class is extensional if and only if it is characterized solely by its membership.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10630430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@More precisely, a class C is extensional if and only if for any class C', if C' has exactly the same members as C, then C and C' are identical.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10630440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If a class does not satisfy this condition, then it is intensional.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10630450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While extensional classes are more well-behaved and well-understood mathematically, as well as less problematic philosophically, they do not permit the fine grained distinctions that ontologies often need to make.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10630460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, an ontology may want to distinguish between the class of all creatures with a kidney and the class of all creatures with a heart, even if these classes happen to have exactly the same members.@1@37@@oe@30-11-2008
10630470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the upper ontologies mentioned above, the classes are defined intensionally.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Intensionally defined classes usually have necessary conditions associated with membership in each class.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10630490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some classes may also have sufficient conditions, and in those cases the combination of necessary and sufficient conditions make that class a fully ''defined'' class.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10630500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Importantly, a class can subsume or be subsumed by other classes; a class subsumed by another is called a ''subclass'' of the subsuming class.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10630510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, ''Vehicle'' subsumes ''Car'', since (necessarily) anything that is a member of the latter class is a member of the former.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10630520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The subsumption relation is used to create a hierarchy of classes, typically with a maximally general class like ''Thing'' at the top, and very specific classes like ''2002 Ford Explorer'' at the bottom.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10630530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The critically important consequence of the subsumption relation is the inheritance of properties from the parent (subsuming) class to the child (subsumed) class.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10630540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus, anything that is necessarily true of a parent class is also necessarily true of all of its subsumed child classes.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10630550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In some ontologies, a class is only allowed to have one parent (''single inheritance''), but in most ontologies, classes are allowed to have any number of parents (''multiple inheritance''), and in the latter case all necessary properties of each parent are inherited by the subsumed child class.@1@47@@oe@30-11-2008
10630560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus a particular class of animal (''HouseCat'') may be a child of the class ''Cat'' and also a child of the class ''Pet''.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10630570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A partition is a set of related classes and associated rules that allow objects to be placed into the appropriate class.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10630580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, to the right is the partial diagram of an ontology that has a partition of the ''Car'' class into the classes ''2-Wheel Drive'' and ''4-Wheel Drive''.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10630590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The partition rule determines if a particular car is placed in the ''2-Wheel Drive'' or the ''4-Wheel Drive'' class.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10630600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If the partition rule(s) guarantee that a single ''Car'' cannot be in both classes, then the partition is called a disjoint partition.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10630610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If the partition rules ensure that every concrete object in the super-class is an instance of at least one of the partition classes, then the partition is called an exhaustive partition.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10630620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Attributes ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10630630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Objects in the ontology can be described by assigning attributes to them.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10630640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Each attribute has at least a name and a value, and is used to store information that is specific to the object it is attached to.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10630650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example the Ford Explorer object has attributes such as:@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10630660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Name'': Ford Explorer@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10630670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Number-of-doors'': 4@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10630680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Engine'': {4.0L, 4.6L}@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10630690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Transmission'': 6-speed@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10630700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The value of an attribute can be a complex [[data type]]; in this example, the value of the attribute called ''Engine'' is a list of values, not just a single value.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10630710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If you did not define attributes for the concepts you would have either a [[taxonomy]] (if [[hyponym]] relationships exist between concepts) or a '''controlled vocabulary'''.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10630720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These are useful, but are not considered true ontologies.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10630730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Relationships===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10630740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An important use of attributes is to describe the relationships (also known as relations) between objects in the ontology.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10630750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Typically a relation is an attribute whose value is another object in the ontology.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10630760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example in the ontology that contains the Ford Explorer and the [[Ford Bronco]], the Ford Bronco object might have the following attribute:@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10630770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* ''Successor'': Ford Explorer@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10630780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This tells us that the Explorer is the model that replaced the Bronco.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10630790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Much of the power of ontologies comes from the ability to describe these relations.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10630800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Together, the set of relations describes the [[semantics]] of the domain.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10630810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The most important type of relation is the [[subsumption]] relation (''is-[[superclass]]-of'', the converse of ''[[is-a]]'', ''is-subtype-of'' or ''is-[[subclass]]-of'').@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10630820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This defines which objects are members of classes of objects.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10630830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example we have already seen that the Ford Explorer ''is-a'' 4-wheel drive, which in turn ''is-a'' Car:@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10630840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The addition of the is-a relationships has created a hierarchical [[taxonomy]]; a tree-like structure (or, more generally, a [[partially ordered set]]) that clearly depicts how objects relate to one another.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10630850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In such a structure, each object is the 'child' of a 'parent class' (Some languages restrict the is-a relationship to one parent for all nodes, but many do not).@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10630860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another common type of relations is the [[meronymy]] relation, written as ''part-of'', that represents how objects combine together to form composite objects.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10630870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, if we extended our example ontology to include objects like Steering Wheel, we would say that "Steering Wheel is-part-of Ford Explorer" since a steering wheel is one of the components of a Ford Explorer.@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10630880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If we introduce meronymy relationships to our ontology, we find that this simple and elegant tree structure quickly becomes complex and significantly more difficult to interpret manually.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10630890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is not difficult to understand why; an entity that is described as 'part of' another entity might also be 'part of' a third entity.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10630900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Consequently, entities may have more than one parent.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10630910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The structure that emerges is known as a [[directed acyclic graph]] (DAG).@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10630920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As well as the standard is-a and part-of relations, ontologies often include additional types of relation that further refine the semantics they model.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10630930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These relations are often domain-specific and are used to answer particular types of question.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10630940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example in the domain of automobiles, we might define a ''made-in'' relationship which tells us where each car is built.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10630950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@So the Ford Explorer is ''made-in'' [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]].@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10630960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The ontology may also know that Louisville is-in [[Kentucky]] and Kentucky is-a state of the [[United States|USA]].@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10630970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Software using this ontology could now answer a question like "which cars are made in the U.S.?"@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10630980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Domain ontologies and upper ontologies ==@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10630990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A domain ontology (or domain-specific ontology) models a specific domain, or part of the world.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10631000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It represents the particular meanings of terms as they apply to that domain.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10631010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example the word ''[[card]]'' has many different meanings.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10631020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An ontology about the domain of [[poker]] would model the "[[playing card]]" meaning of the word, while an ontology about the domain of [[computer hardware]] would model the "[[punch card]]" and "[[video card]]" meanings.@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10631030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An [[Upper ontology (computer science)|upper ontology]] (or foundation ontology) is a model of the common objects that are generally applicable across a wide range of domain ontologies.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10631040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It contains a [[core glossary]] in whose terms objects in a set of domains can be described.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10631050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are several standardized upper ontologies available for use, including [[Dublin Core]], [[General Formal Ontology|GFO]], [[OpenCyc]]/[[ResearchCyc]], [[Suggested Upper Merged Ontology|SUMO]], and [http://www.loa-cnr.it/DOLCE.html DOLCE]l.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10631060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[WordNet]], while considered an upper ontology by some, is not an ontology: it is a unique combination of a [[taxonomy]] and a controlled vocabulary (see above, under Attributes).@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10631070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[Gellish]] ontology is an example of a combination of an upper and a domain ontology.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10631080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Since domain ontologies represent concepts in very specific and often eclectic ways, they are often incompatible.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10631090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As systems that rely on domain ontologies expand, they often need to merge domain ontologies into a more general representation.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10631100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This presents a challenge to the ontology designer.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10631110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Different ontologies in the same domain can also arise due to different perceptions of the domain based on cultural background, education, ideology, or because a different representation language was chosen.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10631120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@At present, merging ontologies is a largely manual process and therefore time-consuming and expensive.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10631130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Using a foundation ontology to provide a common definition of core terms can make this process manageable.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10631140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are studies on generalized techniques for merging ontologies, but this area of research is still largely theoretical.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10631150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Ontology languages ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10631160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An [[ontology language]] is a [[formal language]] used to encode the ontology.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10631170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are a number of such languages for ontologies, both proprietary and standards-based:@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10631180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Web Ontology Language|OWL]] is a language for making ontological statements, developed as a follow-on from [[Resource Description Framework|RDF]] and [[RDFS]], as well as earlier ontology language projects including [[Ontology Inference Layer|OIL]], [[DARPA Agent Markup Language|DAML]] and [[DAMLplusOIL|DAML+OIL]].@1@38@@oe@30-11-2008
10631190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@OWL is intended to be used over the [[World Wide Web]], and all its elements (classes, properties and individuals) are defined as RDF [[resource (Web)|resources]], and identified by [[Uniform Resource Identifier|URI]]s.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10631200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[KIF]] is a syntax for [[first-order logic]] that is based on [[S-expression]]s.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10631210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The [[Cyc]] project has its own ontology language called [[CycL]], based on [[first-order predicate calculus]] with some higher-order extensions.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10631220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Rule Interchange Format]] (RIF) and [[F-Logic]] combine ontologies and rules.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10631230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The [[Gellish]] language includes rules for its own extension and thus integrates an ontology with an ontology language.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10631240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Relation to the philosophical term ==@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10631250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The term ''ontology'' has its origin in [[ontology|philosophy]], where it is the name of one fundamental branch of [[metaphysics]], concerned with analyzing various types or modes of ''existence'', often with special attention to the relations between particulars and universals, between intrinsic and extrinsic properties, and between essence and existence.@1@49@@oe@30-11-2008
10631260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@According to [[Tom Gruber]] at [[Stanford University]], the meaning of ''ontology'' in the context of computer science is “a description of the concepts and relationships that can exist for an [[Software agent|agent]] or a community of agents.”@1@37@@oe@30-11-2008
10631270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@He goes on to specify that an ontology is generally written, “as a set of definitions of formal vocabulary.”@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10631280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@What ontology has in common in both computer science and philosophy is the representation of entities, ideas, and events, along with their properties and relations, according to a system of categories.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10631290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In both fields, one finds considerable work on problems of ontological relativity (e.g.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10631300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Quine]] and [[Kripke]] in philosophy, [[John F. Sowa|Sowa]] and [[Nicola Guarino|Guarino]] in computer science (Top-level ontological categories.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10631310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@By: Sowa, John F.@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10631320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In International Journal of Human-Computer Studies, v. 43 (November/December 1995) p. 669-85.), and debates concerning whether a normative ontology is viable (e.g. debates over [[foundationalism]] in philosophy, debates over the [[Cyc]] project in AI).@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10631330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Differences between the two are largely matters of focus.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10631340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Philosophers are less concerned with establishing fixed, controlled vocabularies than are researchers in computer science, while computer scientists are less involved in discussions of first principles (such as debating whether there are such things as fixed essences, or whether entities must be ontologically more primary than processes).@1@47@@oe@30-11-2008
10631350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@During the second half of the 20th century, philosophers extensively debated the possible methods or approaches to building ontologies, without actually ''building'' any very elaborate ontologies themselves.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10631360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@By contrast, computer scientists were building some large and robust ontologies (such as [[WordNet]] and [[Cyc]]) with comparatively little debate over ''how'' they were built.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10631370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the early years of the 21st century, the interdisciplinary project of [[cognitive science]] has been bringing the two circles of scholars closer together.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10631380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, there is talk of a "computational turn in philosophy" which includes philosophers analyzing the formal ontologies of computer science (sometimes even working directly with the software), while researchers in computer science have been making more references to those philosophers who work on ontology (sometimes with direct consequences for their methods).@1@52@@oe@30-11-2008
10631390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Still, many scholars in both fields are uninvolved in this trend of cognitive science, and continue to work independently of one another, pursuing separately their different concerns.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
